1
00:00:00,153 --> 00:00:01,320
SHARAD JONES: Hey, everyone.

2
00:00:01,320 --> 00:00:02,540
Welcome back.

3
00:00:02,540 --> 00:00:05,960
Today, we're going to get on
to cloud storage officially.

4
00:00:05,960 --> 00:00:07,980
So we've kind of
dabbled in this a bit.

5
00:00:07,980 --> 00:00:10,670
We've talked about EBS volumes
a bit, we've talked about S3

6
00:00:10,670 --> 00:00:13,530
a little bit, but it's been
in kind of a hand-wavy way.

7
00:00:13,530 --> 00:00:16,280
So today, we're going to
really actually deep dive, kind

8
00:00:16,280 --> 00:00:19,490
of formally discuss what goes
into kind of cloud storage

9
00:00:19,490 --> 00:00:22,303
solutions and so
just so you have

10
00:00:22,303 --> 00:00:24,470
the background and the
knowledge necessary to do it.

11
00:00:24,470 --> 00:00:27,180
And we'll try to go through
some examples as well

12
00:00:27,180 --> 00:00:29,940
and potentially even give a
demo if we have some time.

13
00:00:29,940 --> 00:00:31,610
But either way, I
just want to give you

14
00:00:31,610 --> 00:00:35,300
a quick, quick overview of
what cloud storage looks like.

15
00:00:35,300 --> 00:00:39,170
So to begin, let's go full
screen on our slides here,

16
00:00:39,170 --> 00:00:42,590
slide myself out the
way, and perfect.

17
00:00:42,590 --> 00:00:46,190
So first off, we've talked about
now the kind of different types

18
00:00:46,190 --> 00:00:48,900
of storage available in AWS.

19
00:00:48,900 --> 00:00:51,530
So we have kind of our instant--

20
00:00:51,530 --> 00:00:52,790
ephemeral storage.

21
00:00:52,790 --> 00:00:55,290
Actually, I don't know if we
actually talked about that yet.

22
00:00:55,290 --> 00:00:58,130
So let's just take a
second on what that is.

23
00:00:58,130 --> 00:01:02,160
So there exists
some bit of storage

24
00:01:02,160 --> 00:01:09,810
that is associated with your
instance, with the actual--

25
00:01:09,810 --> 00:01:11,915
or with your-- with
your EC2 instance.

26
00:01:11,915 --> 00:01:13,290
When you stand it
up, you'll have

27
00:01:13,290 --> 00:01:16,260
some sort of-- or you'll have
some sort of built in storage

28
00:01:16,260 --> 00:01:19,920
capacity defined by the instance
type and all that good stuff.

29
00:01:19,920 --> 00:01:21,420
But the important
thing to note here

30
00:01:21,420 --> 00:01:23,920
is that storage is
ephemeral, right?

31
00:01:23,920 --> 00:01:26,697
It's temporary.

32
00:01:26,697 --> 00:01:28,530
Once you shut down your
instance or once you

33
00:01:28,530 --> 00:01:32,080
terminate your instance, you'll
lose all that information.

34
00:01:32,080 --> 00:01:34,050
And so that's why we
use the Elastic Block

35
00:01:34,050 --> 00:01:35,490
Store, right, the EBS.

36
00:01:35,490 --> 00:01:36,480
That's persistent.

37
00:01:36,480 --> 00:01:37,660
That's mountable.

38
00:01:37,660 --> 00:01:40,440
So when I stand on my
instance, I can mount an EBS--

39
00:01:40,440 --> 00:01:46,955
an EBS-- an EBS storage
solution to my EC2 instance.

40
00:01:46,955 --> 00:01:49,080
But if I terminate my
instance, I don't necessarily

41
00:01:49,080 --> 00:01:53,040
have to terminate my EBS.

42
00:01:53,040 --> 00:01:55,620
So that's something
to keep in mind there

43
00:01:55,620 --> 00:01:58,320
and just to be aware of.

44
00:01:58,320 --> 00:02:00,090
Then there's Elastic
File Store, which we

45
00:02:00,090 --> 00:02:01,382
said is kind of a shared drive.

46
00:02:01,382 --> 00:02:04,150
So it's EBS, but shared
across a bunch of people.

47
00:02:04,150 --> 00:02:06,900
And then there's
S3, which is kind

48
00:02:06,900 --> 00:02:09,740
of the persistent but
object-based storage.

49
00:02:09,740 --> 00:02:11,490
And we'll talk about
this concept of block

50
00:02:11,490 --> 00:02:13,500
versus object-based storage.

51
00:02:13,500 --> 00:02:15,750
But that's going to be
available through a URL and it

52
00:02:15,750 --> 00:02:17,730
can be accessed from anywhere--

53
00:02:17,730 --> 00:02:19,480
well, anywhere that you allow.

54
00:02:19,480 --> 00:02:21,330
You can obviously
restrict solutions there

55
00:02:21,330 --> 00:02:22,572
or restrict access.

56
00:02:22,572 --> 00:02:24,030
And then finally,
there's Glacier--

57
00:02:24,030 --> 00:02:25,560
if I duck out of the way--

58
00:02:25,560 --> 00:02:26,940
Amazon S3 Glacier.

59
00:02:26,940 --> 00:02:29,145
And like we said, that's
referred to as Glacier

60
00:02:29,145 --> 00:02:30,520
because it's cold
storage, right?

61
00:02:30,520 --> 00:02:32,270
That's stuff that's
not access frequently.

62
00:02:32,270 --> 00:02:33,150
That's backups.

63
00:02:33,150 --> 00:02:34,230
That's redundant copies.

64
00:02:34,230 --> 00:02:35,730
That's just something
that's sitting

65
00:02:35,730 --> 00:02:42,150
there, lower cost, but not
as fast, so those trade-offs.

66
00:02:42,150 --> 00:02:45,660
So starting on EBS, I want
to officially say or discuss

67
00:02:45,660 --> 00:02:49,230
what the difference between
block and object store is.

68
00:02:49,230 --> 00:02:52,480
You can think about it
like these squares here.

69
00:02:52,480 --> 00:02:57,540
Imagine these squares are some
file, a text file, let's say.

70
00:02:57,540 --> 00:03:00,100
And let's say you want to change
one character in it, right?

71
00:03:00,100 --> 00:03:03,810
It's a text file that's maybe,
you know, a bunch of usernames.

72
00:03:03,810 --> 00:03:07,830
And you want to change one of
the usernames by one letter.

73
00:03:07,830 --> 00:03:11,610
Well, with block storage,
like we have with EBS,

74
00:03:11,610 --> 00:03:13,800
that's-- you physically
change that one letter

75
00:03:13,800 --> 00:03:16,288
and that's the only thing that
changes in the file, right?

76
00:03:16,288 --> 00:03:18,330
It's exactly like if you
were manipulating a file

77
00:03:18,330 --> 00:03:19,580
on your local computer, right?

78
00:03:19,580 --> 00:03:21,990
You could open up a text file,
make a change and save it,

79
00:03:21,990 --> 00:03:24,407
and it would just continue
going through like that, right?

80
00:03:24,407 --> 00:03:27,870
It's effectively just operating
on that open copy of it.

81
00:03:27,870 --> 00:03:31,330
Object storage with S3,
that's a bit different.

82
00:03:31,330 --> 00:03:34,470
So with object storage,
we're storing everything

83
00:03:34,470 --> 00:03:37,440
as one big unit,
one entire file.

84
00:03:37,440 --> 00:03:39,900
And if I want to change
it, if I want to update it,

85
00:03:39,900 --> 00:03:44,920
I basically need to download it,
change it, and then re-upload

86
00:03:44,920 --> 00:03:46,160
the entire file.

87
00:03:46,160 --> 00:03:48,710
So this is not me operating
directly on the file.

88
00:03:48,710 --> 00:03:51,610
This is me just physically
removing the file completely

89
00:03:51,610 --> 00:03:53,920
and putting it back up there.

90
00:03:53,920 --> 00:03:56,680
This is important to keep in
mind because let's imagine

91
00:03:56,680 --> 00:03:59,530
you have a very, very
large file that you need

92
00:03:59,530 --> 00:04:01,340
to make constant updates to.

93
00:04:01,340 --> 00:04:04,900
You might need to rethink the
way you store it in S3 such

94
00:04:04,900 --> 00:04:06,970
that maybe you do something
where you break it

95
00:04:06,970 --> 00:04:08,560
up into multiple
smaller files that

96
00:04:08,560 --> 00:04:11,290
are easy to manipulate
or identify,

97
00:04:11,290 --> 00:04:12,640
or you do something other--

98
00:04:12,640 --> 00:04:14,223
or something else
that doesn't require

99
00:04:14,223 --> 00:04:18,100
you to do this constant upload
and download and deletion

100
00:04:18,100 --> 00:04:19,300
of an object in S3, right?

101
00:04:19,300 --> 00:04:20,890
Because you do pay
for that sometimes,

102
00:04:20,890 --> 00:04:22,390
or depending on the type of--

103
00:04:22,390 --> 00:04:24,400
or the type of
storage class you're

104
00:04:24,400 --> 00:04:26,942
using, which we'll talk about
those different ones again here

105
00:04:26,942 --> 00:04:27,790
in a little bit.

106
00:04:27,790 --> 00:04:29,800
But that is something
to keep in mind.

107
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:36,190
So the trade-off there again is,
you know, object storage is--

108
00:04:36,190 --> 00:04:40,450
I wouldn't say better, but it
is cheaper and usually more

109
00:04:40,450 --> 00:04:41,490
scalable.

110
00:04:41,490 --> 00:04:43,840
It's easier to define for
these large scale storage

111
00:04:43,840 --> 00:04:45,920
operations versus block store.

112
00:04:45,920 --> 00:04:47,990
That's for, I'm
operating on my computer.

113
00:04:47,990 --> 00:04:50,490
I need to be making constant
changes back and forth from it,

114
00:04:50,490 --> 00:04:50,990
right?

115
00:04:50,990 --> 00:04:52,370
I'm operating on my hard drive.

116
00:04:52,370 --> 00:04:55,060
Kind of think about
it like if you're

117
00:04:55,060 --> 00:04:56,440
working on your local computer.

118
00:04:56,440 --> 00:05:00,790
And you were-- you had
your just hard drive that's

119
00:05:00,790 --> 00:05:03,730
on your computer, your-- maybe
your removable hard drive

120
00:05:03,730 --> 00:05:05,420
or flash drive
that's plugged in.

121
00:05:05,420 --> 00:05:06,920
That's kind of like
your block store, right?

122
00:05:06,920 --> 00:05:08,670
You're just making
changes on those files.

123
00:05:08,670 --> 00:05:10,030
They sit on your computer.

124
00:05:10,030 --> 00:05:12,520
Object storage is I'm
physically sending

125
00:05:12,520 --> 00:05:14,582
that file off to Google Drive.

126
00:05:14,582 --> 00:05:16,540
And when I want to make
a change to that file--

127
00:05:16,540 --> 00:05:18,683
ignore the fact that
Google Docs exists--

128
00:05:18,683 --> 00:05:20,350
if I want to make a
change to that file,

129
00:05:20,350 --> 00:05:22,270
I make a change on my
computer, and then I

130
00:05:22,270 --> 00:05:23,900
re-upload the file entirely.

131
00:05:23,900 --> 00:05:26,480
I don't just operate
directly on it.

132
00:05:26,480 --> 00:05:27,710
And so that's the difference.

133
00:05:27,710 --> 00:05:29,750
That's the block storage
versus object storage.

134
00:05:29,750 --> 00:05:31,470
And again, pros
and cons to both.

135
00:05:35,010 --> 00:05:39,180
The EBS storage solutions, those
individual storage volumes,

136
00:05:39,180 --> 00:05:41,730
they can be attached to one
instance at a time though.

137
00:05:41,730 --> 00:05:44,490
So remember we said-- and
we'll talk about it again too--

138
00:05:44,490 --> 00:05:47,340
EFS is for if we want to attach
it to multiple instances.

139
00:05:47,340 --> 00:05:49,375
EBS is only your computer.

140
00:05:49,375 --> 00:05:50,500
Again, it's one hard drive.

141
00:05:50,500 --> 00:05:52,760
It's got one plug, one
plug coming out of it.

142
00:05:52,760 --> 00:05:55,770
And so it can only
go into one computer.

143
00:05:55,770 --> 00:05:57,100
And so just be mindful of that.

144
00:05:57,100 --> 00:05:59,220
If there's anything that needs
to be shared across users,

145
00:05:59,220 --> 00:06:00,887
EBS won't really work
for that, or if it

146
00:06:00,887 --> 00:06:04,370
needs to be shared across
multiple users at the same time.

147
00:06:04,370 --> 00:06:06,120
It is going to be
automatically replicated

148
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:07,480
within its availability zone.

149
00:06:07,480 --> 00:06:10,380
So it's going to have some
redundant storage there.

150
00:06:10,380 --> 00:06:13,860
So you will have that kind
of extra layer of security.

151
00:06:13,860 --> 00:06:16,530
You can obviously replicate
across availability zones

152
00:06:16,530 --> 00:06:19,662
or across regions even if you
wanted to, if that's important.

153
00:06:19,662 --> 00:06:21,870
Another nice feature that
we didn't really talk about

154
00:06:21,870 --> 00:06:24,910
is that you can automatically
back them up to S3.

155
00:06:24,910 --> 00:06:30,510
So let's say you work
daily on your EC2 instance

156
00:06:30,510 --> 00:06:34,120
and you want to ensure that
you don't lose the data that's

157
00:06:34,120 --> 00:06:35,900
on your EBS volume.

158
00:06:35,900 --> 00:06:38,170
So what you can do is
you can just set it up

159
00:06:38,170 --> 00:06:39,580
to have this automatic--

160
00:06:39,580 --> 00:06:43,180
every eight hours, right,
every workday, let's say,

161
00:06:43,180 --> 00:06:46,630
it takes a snapshot
of your EBS volume

162
00:06:46,630 --> 00:06:49,100
and just uploads it
to your S3 bucket.

163
00:06:49,100 --> 00:06:51,878
And just every day, it does the
same thing, that same process.

164
00:06:51,878 --> 00:06:53,920
And so that gives you that
kind of confidence of,

165
00:06:53,920 --> 00:06:58,570
again, I got the backup and
the redundancy on the storage,

166
00:06:58,570 --> 00:07:03,890
but I don't have to do this
manual process of backing it up.

167
00:07:03,890 --> 00:07:07,870
So it's just another
feature you can do there.

168
00:07:07,870 --> 00:07:09,610
And so, yeah, we've
talked about plenty

169
00:07:09,610 --> 00:07:11,930
of ways you can use it,
you know, boot volumes.

170
00:07:11,930 --> 00:07:13,990
So I'm booting from
that EBS, which

171
00:07:13,990 --> 00:07:17,050
I can do so I can have all
my files from my boot process

172
00:07:17,050 --> 00:07:18,670
stored on the EBS volume.

173
00:07:18,670 --> 00:07:23,830
Storage for data or for files,
I can host databases on EBS

174
00:07:23,830 --> 00:07:25,670
if they're fast
enough to do that

175
00:07:25,670 --> 00:07:28,330
or you can choose ones that
are fast enough to do that,

176
00:07:28,330 --> 00:07:30,495
enterprise applications,
all kinds of good stuff.

177
00:07:33,040 --> 00:07:35,660
So kind of the breakdown of
the different volume types,

178
00:07:35,660 --> 00:07:39,290
we saw this when we were going
through the EC2 setup process.

179
00:07:39,290 --> 00:07:41,680
We saw that we could choose
these different types of EBS

180
00:07:41,680 --> 00:07:44,377
volumes.

181
00:07:44,377 --> 00:07:46,460
Oh, sorry, it's always
difficult to point on this.

182
00:07:46,460 --> 00:07:47,440
It's mirrored.

183
00:07:47,440 --> 00:07:48,980
We use the general
purpose, right?

184
00:07:48,980 --> 00:07:51,190
So we did that one
before that first column.

185
00:07:51,190 --> 00:07:54,880
And that's the GP2
and GP3 options.

186
00:07:54,880 --> 00:07:56,620
Those are going to
be your standard ones

187
00:07:56,620 --> 00:07:58,270
to go to for most operations.

188
00:07:58,270 --> 00:07:59,510
You can boot from them.

189
00:07:59,510 --> 00:08:02,102
So they are a
functional boot volume.

190
00:08:02,102 --> 00:08:04,060
And again, if I'm confusing
with the word boot,

191
00:08:04,060 --> 00:08:07,540
I physically mean when I boot up
a computer, it's booting from--

192
00:08:07,540 --> 00:08:11,120
or I can choose such that it
boots from that EBS volume.

193
00:08:11,120 --> 00:08:13,880
So that if I have an operating
system or files or whatever,

194
00:08:13,880 --> 00:08:17,050
or some opening or launch
procedure stored on that EBS

195
00:08:17,050 --> 00:08:19,880
volume, that's what happens
when I boot up the computer.

196
00:08:19,880 --> 00:08:21,290
So it can be a boot volume.

197
00:08:21,290 --> 00:08:24,100
It's fast enough for that.

198
00:08:24,100 --> 00:08:27,130
You can use them for virtual
desktops, low latency

199
00:08:27,130 --> 00:08:30,110
applications, dev and
test environments.

200
00:08:30,110 --> 00:08:32,289
So they're kind of
just your go-to.

201
00:08:32,289 --> 00:08:33,988
If you don't have a
preference one way

202
00:08:33,988 --> 00:08:35,530
or another of what
it should be doing

203
00:08:35,530 --> 00:08:37,450
or you don't really know exactly
what you're using it for,

204
00:08:37,450 --> 00:08:39,700
you just kind of need
something for general purpose,

205
00:08:39,700 --> 00:08:42,429
go with that GP category.

206
00:08:42,429 --> 00:08:44,350
The provisioned IOPS--

207
00:08:44,350 --> 00:08:46,570
IOPS stands for, I believe,
input/output operations

208
00:08:46,570 --> 00:08:47,510
per second.

209
00:08:47,510 --> 00:08:50,350
So that is when
you're trying to have

210
00:08:50,350 --> 00:08:52,360
something that has a lot of--

211
00:08:52,360 --> 00:08:54,880
requires sustained
IOPS performance,

212
00:08:54,880 --> 00:08:56,660
right, it's just a
bunch of input/output.

213
00:08:56,660 --> 00:09:03,910
So you're constantly writing
to and from your EBS volume.

214
00:09:03,910 --> 00:09:05,240
The word slipped my mind there.

215
00:09:05,240 --> 00:09:07,792
You're constantly writing
to and from your EBS volume.

216
00:09:07,792 --> 00:09:09,500
This is something you
want to use, right?

217
00:09:09,500 --> 00:09:12,550
These provisioned IOPS are
a good solution for that.

218
00:09:12,550 --> 00:09:15,500
An example of that is really
large database workloads, right?

219
00:09:15,500 --> 00:09:17,770
If you have a massive
database that your customers

220
00:09:17,770 --> 00:09:21,730
or your employees are using
that they're constantly

221
00:09:21,730 --> 00:09:24,288
writing to and from,
provisioned IOPS

222
00:09:24,288 --> 00:09:26,080
is going to be much,
much faster than using

223
00:09:26,080 --> 00:09:27,230
any of these other solutions.

224
00:09:27,230 --> 00:09:28,592
So that's what that's there for.

225
00:09:28,592 --> 00:09:30,800
But, obviously, you do pay
a slight premium for that.

226
00:09:30,800 --> 00:09:33,310
So it's always a
case of considering

227
00:09:33,310 --> 00:09:38,080
your needs at the time and
optimizing the solution there.

228
00:09:38,080 --> 00:09:40,970
Then for hard disk drives,
you can choose those as well.

229
00:09:40,970 --> 00:09:43,510
But note that neither the
hard disk drive solutions

230
00:09:43,510 --> 00:09:45,348
can be used as boot volumes.

231
00:09:45,348 --> 00:09:46,640
It's really due to time, right?

232
00:09:46,640 --> 00:09:47,650
They're slow.

233
00:09:47,650 --> 00:09:49,970
Historically, we have booted
off of hard disk drives.

234
00:09:49,970 --> 00:09:51,928
You might even have a
computer still that boots

235
00:09:51,928 --> 00:09:52,990
off of a hard disk drive.

236
00:09:52,990 --> 00:09:54,370
It's just very slow.

237
00:09:54,370 --> 00:09:56,770
Most modern laptops
and computers

238
00:09:56,770 --> 00:10:00,220
have switched to using a solid
state drive of some sort,

239
00:10:00,220 --> 00:10:04,850
whether it be NVMe two-slot
or something like that.

240
00:10:04,850 --> 00:10:07,480
They try to maximize the--

241
00:10:07,480 --> 00:10:10,445
or use the fastest memory
they can for the boot volume.

242
00:10:10,445 --> 00:10:12,070
And then you can
still have a hard disk

243
00:10:12,070 --> 00:10:14,840
drive as your backup
big data storage.

244
00:10:14,840 --> 00:10:18,400
Because those are cheaper
per gigabyte than solid state

245
00:10:18,400 --> 00:10:20,423
drives at the cost of speed.

246
00:10:20,423 --> 00:10:22,340
And so that's exactly
how they're used, right?

247
00:10:22,340 --> 00:10:25,900
So those throughput optimized
ones are still decently fast.

248
00:10:25,900 --> 00:10:27,890
So you can use them for
streaming workloads.

249
00:10:27,890 --> 00:10:31,990
So if you had, for example,
streaming web data, right,

250
00:10:31,990 --> 00:10:33,715
you had all the clicks
on your website,

251
00:10:33,715 --> 00:10:36,752
and you have a massive website,
you could use it for that.

252
00:10:36,752 --> 00:10:38,710
It's going to be fast
enough, more than likely,

253
00:10:38,710 --> 00:10:41,740
for it-- depends on
your website for sure.

254
00:10:41,740 --> 00:10:44,380
But, again, the real
benefit is they're

255
00:10:44,380 --> 00:10:47,200
much cheaper per gigabyte
than your equivalent

256
00:10:47,200 --> 00:10:48,110
solid state drives.

257
00:10:48,110 --> 00:10:50,380
And so they're great
for those big data

258
00:10:50,380 --> 00:10:52,512
workloads, data warehouses.

259
00:10:52,512 --> 00:10:54,220
When you have a bunch
of logs, right, you

260
00:10:54,220 --> 00:10:57,280
have an app or something
that's hosted in the cloud,

261
00:10:57,280 --> 00:10:59,020
you can use one of
these hard disk drives

262
00:10:59,020 --> 00:11:01,100
to store all of your logs.

263
00:11:01,100 --> 00:11:03,400
So that way, if something
breaks or there's some issue,

264
00:11:03,400 --> 00:11:05,890
you can go back through
them, but you're not

265
00:11:05,890 --> 00:11:09,573
paying a ton of money for
storing all those logs.

266
00:11:09,573 --> 00:11:11,740
And then there's obviously
the cold storage, kind of

267
00:11:11,740 --> 00:11:15,940
similar to how we talked about
with Glacier in that these are

268
00:11:15,940 --> 00:11:18,855
kind of known to not--
or when something's not

269
00:11:18,855 --> 00:11:20,230
going to be
frequently accessed--

270
00:11:20,230 --> 00:11:22,313
and maybe even logs kind
of fall into that bucket.

271
00:11:22,313 --> 00:11:24,548
Maybe you're fairly
confident, it's a mature app.

272
00:11:24,548 --> 00:11:26,590
You probably don't need
to access the logs often,

273
00:11:26,590 --> 00:11:27,923
but you still want to have them.

274
00:11:27,923 --> 00:11:30,550
You can put them
into cold storage.

275
00:11:30,550 --> 00:11:33,450
And, again, sacrifice
is always speed, right?

276
00:11:33,450 --> 00:11:36,050
So it's this trade-off
between speed and cost

277
00:11:36,050 --> 00:11:37,590
at almost every turn.

278
00:11:37,590 --> 00:11:41,575
So that's just a
thing to think about.

279
00:11:41,575 --> 00:11:43,700
So we've talked about the
fact that, first off, you

280
00:11:43,700 --> 00:11:46,050
can snapshot your
EBS volumes, right?

281
00:11:46,050 --> 00:11:47,870
So you can set
that on a schedule

282
00:11:47,870 --> 00:11:49,790
or you can manually do it.

283
00:11:49,790 --> 00:11:52,140
You can recreate your
volume from a snapshot.

284
00:11:52,140 --> 00:11:54,650
So when you go into
create an EBS volume,

285
00:11:54,650 --> 00:11:57,440
you can actually select to
choose a snapshot at that time

286
00:11:57,440 --> 00:11:58,580
that you want to--

287
00:11:58,580 --> 00:11:59,960
or snapshot from
S3 that you want

288
00:11:59,960 --> 00:12:02,990
to use to create
this volume from.

289
00:12:02,990 --> 00:12:06,260
You can copy them, share
them to different regions

290
00:12:06,260 --> 00:12:08,420
for extra bit of reliability.

291
00:12:08,420 --> 00:12:11,180
You can encrypt the data
that is being transferred

292
00:12:11,180 --> 00:12:13,760
between your EC2 instance
and the EBS volume

293
00:12:13,760 --> 00:12:16,800
within a data center as well
too for no additional cost.

294
00:12:16,800 --> 00:12:18,957
So if you need that
extra layer of security

295
00:12:18,957 --> 00:12:20,540
or, again, there's
no additional cost,

296
00:12:20,540 --> 00:12:22,580
if you just want that
extra layer of security,

297
00:12:22,580 --> 00:12:23,790
throw it on there.

298
00:12:23,790 --> 00:12:26,390
And then any transfer
of information

299
00:12:26,390 --> 00:12:28,887
is encrypted such
that if somebody

300
00:12:28,887 --> 00:12:31,220
were to inject themselves in
the middle of that transfer

301
00:12:31,220 --> 00:12:33,950
between your EC2 instance
and your EBS volume,

302
00:12:33,950 --> 00:12:36,257
they would not be
able to decrypt,

303
00:12:36,257 --> 00:12:38,840
or at least should not be able
to decrypt the information that

304
00:12:38,840 --> 00:12:39,780
is making that transfer.

305
00:12:39,780 --> 00:12:42,280
Because, again, we've been kind
of talking about it as like,

306
00:12:42,280 --> 00:12:45,470
OK, this is an EBS instance
directly plugged into your--

307
00:12:45,470 --> 00:12:48,330
or an EBS volume directly
plugged into your EC2 instance.

308
00:12:48,330 --> 00:12:50,870
That's not technically true.

309
00:12:50,870 --> 00:12:54,360
These are servers sitting
in a massive data center.

310
00:12:54,360 --> 00:12:58,273
And so they're not going to be
directly, directly connected

311
00:12:58,273 --> 00:13:00,440
or kind of directly plugged
in, kind of isolated air

312
00:13:00,440 --> 00:13:02,010
gapped from other solutions.

313
00:13:02,010 --> 00:13:03,930
They will go through
some network processing.

314
00:13:03,930 --> 00:13:06,170
And so, therefore,
you can encrypt them

315
00:13:06,170 --> 00:13:08,840
when they're making that
transition from your instance

316
00:13:08,840 --> 00:13:10,460
to your volume.

317
00:13:10,460 --> 00:13:13,220
It's unlikely that there will
be a risk there, but, again--

318
00:13:13,220 --> 00:13:14,210
and you might even
have some things

319
00:13:14,210 --> 00:13:15,480
where that's required, right?

320
00:13:15,480 --> 00:13:19,160
It might be that you work for--
or work on some sensitive data

321
00:13:19,160 --> 00:13:22,850
and legal requirements insist
that if your data is transferred

322
00:13:22,850 --> 00:13:25,970
between any two sources
or any two locations,

323
00:13:25,970 --> 00:13:27,800
they have to be
encrypted in transit.

324
00:13:27,800 --> 00:13:30,330
That is available as
an option in there.

325
00:13:30,330 --> 00:13:32,052
So keep that in mind.

326
00:13:32,052 --> 00:13:33,510
And then finally,
it's really nice.

327
00:13:33,510 --> 00:13:34,350
They are elastic.

328
00:13:34,350 --> 00:13:37,070
So slide myself over here now.

329
00:13:37,070 --> 00:13:40,000
What we mean by elastic is that
you can change them, resize

330
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:43,390
them, add new volumes
on the fly dynamically

331
00:13:43,390 --> 00:13:44,870
without stopping your instance.

332
00:13:44,870 --> 00:13:46,990
It's, again, exactly like
if I had a flash drive

333
00:13:46,990 --> 00:13:48,250
and I plugged it
into my computer.

334
00:13:48,250 --> 00:13:50,083
And then I say, oh, I
need some more memory.

335
00:13:50,083 --> 00:13:52,390
I'm going to plug-in a
different, bigger flash drive.

336
00:13:52,390 --> 00:13:54,310
Or I'm going to take
this flash drive off

337
00:13:54,310 --> 00:13:56,435
because I'm going to need
it somewhere else, right?

338
00:13:56,435 --> 00:13:58,540
Maybe I'm working on
my instance and I'm

339
00:13:58,540 --> 00:14:01,060
having an EBS volume
attached, but then my coworker

340
00:14:01,060 --> 00:14:03,110
needs access to something
on that EBS volume.

341
00:14:03,110 --> 00:14:05,952
I can detach it and attach it
to their computer too, right?

342
00:14:05,952 --> 00:14:07,660
It can only be attached
to one at a time,

343
00:14:07,660 --> 00:14:09,587
but I can do that on
the fly dynamically

344
00:14:09,587 --> 00:14:12,170
without having to shut down my
instance or anything like that,

345
00:14:12,170 --> 00:14:14,890
so.

346
00:14:14,890 --> 00:14:18,670
OK, so then on to S3.

347
00:14:18,670 --> 00:14:22,210
So Amazon S3, simple
storage service.

348
00:14:22,210 --> 00:14:23,980
So some quick fast
facts on this,

349
00:14:23,980 --> 00:14:25,917
some bullet points,
the reason I kind

350
00:14:25,917 --> 00:14:28,000
go through a lot of these
bullet points is, again,

351
00:14:28,000 --> 00:14:30,400
a lot of these questions,
a lot of these points

352
00:14:30,400 --> 00:14:32,890
are questions on the--

353
00:14:32,890 --> 00:14:35,608
or potential questions on
the certification exam.

354
00:14:35,608 --> 00:14:37,400
So if that's something
you want to explore,

355
00:14:37,400 --> 00:14:40,040
I want to make sure you see
some of these bullet point facts

356
00:14:40,040 --> 00:14:41,550
that they expect you to know.

357
00:14:41,550 --> 00:14:44,630
So as we talked
about, though, S3

358
00:14:44,630 --> 00:14:46,310
is object level
storage as opposed

359
00:14:46,310 --> 00:14:47,640
to block level storage, right?

360
00:14:47,640 --> 00:14:50,130
EBS, elastic block
storage, is block storage.

361
00:14:50,130 --> 00:14:52,242
S3 is object storage.

362
00:14:52,242 --> 00:14:54,200
And so that means, again,
if you make a change,

363
00:14:54,200 --> 00:14:56,750
you're going to need to
re-upload the entire modified

364
00:14:56,750 --> 00:14:57,360
file.

365
00:14:57,360 --> 00:14:59,180
You can't just make
a change on the spot

366
00:14:59,180 --> 00:15:02,480
to that specific
portion of the file.

367
00:15:02,480 --> 00:15:05,340
All S3 objects are
stored in buckets.

368
00:15:05,340 --> 00:15:10,010
So that's-- it's just the
name, the nomenclature they use

369
00:15:10,010 --> 00:15:10,710
for it.

370
00:15:10,710 --> 00:15:12,500
It looks kind of
like a file system.

371
00:15:12,500 --> 00:15:14,000
And let me see real
quick if we have

372
00:15:14,000 --> 00:15:16,470
plans to go through
a tutorial on this.

373
00:15:16,470 --> 00:15:17,605
I think we do.

374
00:15:21,188 --> 00:15:23,730
I might actually, though, just
open up your eyes in a second.

375
00:15:23,730 --> 00:15:26,270
And once we finish this,
I'll open up S3 and show you

376
00:15:26,270 --> 00:15:29,870
how to access a bucket
and what that looks like.

377
00:15:29,870 --> 00:15:33,300
But either way, bucket
names are universal.

378
00:15:33,300 --> 00:15:36,420
So it has to be unique
across the entirety of S3.

379
00:15:36,420 --> 00:15:40,730
So all users that use AWS, there
can be no duplicate bucket names

380
00:15:40,730 --> 00:15:44,610
because S3 buckets
are accessed via URL.

381
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:47,640
So that URL is going to
be unique to your bucket.

382
00:15:47,640 --> 00:15:49,340
Therefore, it
needs to be unique.

383
00:15:49,340 --> 00:15:51,240
But it's not as bad
as it seems, right?

384
00:15:51,240 --> 00:15:53,550
I mean, you can imagine
there are infinite names

385
00:15:53,550 --> 00:15:54,800
that you could name something.

386
00:15:54,800 --> 00:15:56,630
So you could always just add
one, two, three, four, five,

387
00:15:56,630 --> 00:15:59,480
whatever the number is at the
end until you get to a point

388
00:15:59,480 --> 00:16:01,020
where your bucket
is uniquely named

389
00:16:01,020 --> 00:16:05,240
if you have some common name
that you're using for it.

390
00:16:05,240 --> 00:16:09,860
You basically have
unlimited storage capacity.

391
00:16:09,860 --> 00:16:11,580
I don't like to use
the word unlimited.

392
00:16:11,580 --> 00:16:13,280
They use the word unlimited.

393
00:16:13,280 --> 00:16:15,050
It's obviously
constrained by however big

394
00:16:15,050 --> 00:16:16,320
their server farms are.

395
00:16:16,320 --> 00:16:19,190
But by the time you
upload enough data

396
00:16:19,190 --> 00:16:22,040
or you go through the process of
uploading enough data that they

397
00:16:22,040 --> 00:16:23,922
run out of storage,
you can probably

398
00:16:23,922 --> 00:16:25,880
assume that they would
have upped their storage

399
00:16:25,880 --> 00:16:28,642
capacity to match the demands
of you as a customer, right?

400
00:16:28,642 --> 00:16:30,350
You'd be paying so
much money in storage,

401
00:16:30,350 --> 00:16:32,630
they'd probably just use that
to then build some more storage

402
00:16:32,630 --> 00:16:33,760
or some more data centers.

403
00:16:33,760 --> 00:16:38,070
So for all practical purposes,
it is unlimited data storage.

404
00:16:38,070 --> 00:16:42,060
But a single object is
limited to 5 terabytes.

405
00:16:42,060 --> 00:16:46,800
So, for example, if you have
a snapshot of your EBS volume

406
00:16:46,800 --> 00:16:50,700
or a snapshot of a database,
those are single objects.

407
00:16:50,700 --> 00:16:52,290
A snapshot would
be a single object

408
00:16:52,290 --> 00:16:54,340
if you design it that way.

409
00:16:54,340 --> 00:16:56,640
And so keep in
mind that can only

410
00:16:56,640 --> 00:16:59,100
be up to 5 terabytes
in size, which

411
00:16:59,100 --> 00:17:00,310
is a massive amount of data.

412
00:17:00,310 --> 00:17:01,590
So it's likely not a huge issue.

413
00:17:01,590 --> 00:17:02,965
But you might have
some databases

414
00:17:02,965 --> 00:17:06,510
that could get close to that
number, and so something

415
00:17:06,510 --> 00:17:08,194
to keep in mind.

416
00:17:08,194 --> 00:17:09,569
As with everything
else, designed

417
00:17:09,569 --> 00:17:12,060
with 11 nines of
durability, so set something

418
00:17:12,060 --> 00:17:15,395
like in a billion objects
or in a billion years,

419
00:17:15,395 --> 00:17:17,770
a million objects, something
like that, you may lose one.

420
00:17:17,770 --> 00:17:19,619
So, basically, you're
not going to need

421
00:17:19,619 --> 00:17:21,369
to worry about durability.

422
00:17:21,369 --> 00:17:24,000
You're not going
to lose any files.

423
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:27,480
Data is stored redundantly
across multiple facilities,

424
00:17:27,480 --> 00:17:30,930
i.e. multiple data centers,
and then multiple devices each

425
00:17:30,930 --> 00:17:32,920
in-- within each data center.

426
00:17:32,920 --> 00:17:36,480
So it's not just that it's on
one machine in that data center,

427
00:17:36,480 --> 00:17:37,930
it's on multiple machines.

428
00:17:37,930 --> 00:17:41,730
And then they replicate that
across multiple data centers

429
00:17:41,730 --> 00:17:42,370
as well too.

430
00:17:42,370 --> 00:17:46,120
So a lot of redundancy, a lot
of security in the storage.

431
00:17:46,120 --> 00:17:48,260
So I wouldn't worry
about it at all.

432
00:17:51,570 --> 00:17:53,890
Object can be
basically any type--

433
00:17:53,890 --> 00:17:57,840
so images, videos, texts, logs,
lists, your favorite file type.

434
00:17:57,840 --> 00:18:00,030
Anything that is a file
that is stored on a computer

435
00:18:00,030 --> 00:18:01,155
can be stored there, right?

436
00:18:01,155 --> 00:18:03,000
Doesn't matter the file ending.

437
00:18:03,000 --> 00:18:06,870
Again, as long as it's less than
5 terabytes for a single object,

438
00:18:06,870 --> 00:18:08,707
it's good to upload there.

439
00:18:08,707 --> 00:18:10,290
And then, yeah,
you're going to access

440
00:18:10,290 --> 00:18:14,040
everything via HTTP or HTTPS.

441
00:18:14,040 --> 00:18:15,415
So it's just going
to be via URL.

442
00:18:15,415 --> 00:18:17,082
And we'll see that
in a little bit here.

443
00:18:17,082 --> 00:18:18,660
And then yeah, you
can use your IAM,

444
00:18:18,660 --> 00:18:20,340
your identity and
access management

445
00:18:20,340 --> 00:18:23,820
controls to limit
who can access which

446
00:18:23,820 --> 00:18:30,750
objects within a bucket or even
the whole bucket together, so.

447
00:18:30,750 --> 00:18:32,417
Then we talked a
little bit about these,

448
00:18:32,417 --> 00:18:34,083
but I want to go
through them one by one

449
00:18:34,083 --> 00:18:36,300
just so you can get a sense
of what they're used for,

450
00:18:36,300 --> 00:18:39,120
why you'd want to use them, and
the formal kind of definition

451
00:18:39,120 --> 00:18:39,700
of them.

452
00:18:39,700 --> 00:18:43,050
So the different tiers of--

453
00:18:43,050 --> 00:18:45,250
or different classes
of S3 storage.

454
00:18:45,250 --> 00:18:47,760
So the standard class, the
one you'll probably use more

455
00:18:47,760 --> 00:18:50,880
than anything else, that's
just the go-to default.

456
00:18:50,880 --> 00:18:54,250
High durability, availability,
low latency, high throughput,

457
00:18:54,250 --> 00:18:58,560
it's kind of the fastest
solution, technically,

458
00:18:58,560 --> 00:19:00,810
amongst S3 options.

459
00:19:00,810 --> 00:19:04,080
And while that does mean
it's the most expensive,

460
00:19:04,080 --> 00:19:06,340
the cost is still really,
really low for that.

461
00:19:06,340 --> 00:19:09,180
I think we talked some
about that already.

462
00:19:09,180 --> 00:19:11,940
And so you can use it in
basically really any application

463
00:19:11,940 --> 00:19:13,677
where you need all
those features, right?

464
00:19:13,677 --> 00:19:14,760
You need that low latency.

465
00:19:14,760 --> 00:19:17,010
You need that high throughput.

466
00:19:17,010 --> 00:19:18,550
So I'll give you
an example, right?

467
00:19:18,550 --> 00:19:20,730
You're designing an Airbnb
website or a website

468
00:19:20,730 --> 00:19:23,760
similar to Airbnb and you
need to display images

469
00:19:23,760 --> 00:19:26,200
for every single rental
dynamically, right?

470
00:19:26,200 --> 00:19:28,050
If you've ever
gone on Airbnb, you

471
00:19:28,050 --> 00:19:31,860
know you can tap on any
location, any rental

472
00:19:31,860 --> 00:19:34,630
and pull up all the images in
probably a fraction of a second,

473
00:19:34,630 --> 00:19:35,130
right?

474
00:19:35,130 --> 00:19:38,610
There's no lag time, really
no noticeable lag time there,

475
00:19:38,610 --> 00:19:40,630
assuming you have a good
internet connection.

476
00:19:40,630 --> 00:19:43,038
And that's done by likely--

477
00:19:43,038 --> 00:19:44,580
I mean, I can't
guarantee exactly how

478
00:19:44,580 --> 00:19:45,997
these companies
store everything--

479
00:19:45,997 --> 00:19:49,320
but it's almost certainly
S3 or an equivalent tool

480
00:19:49,320 --> 00:19:51,750
from another cloud provider.

481
00:19:51,750 --> 00:19:53,430
And so, again, if
you look at the code

482
00:19:53,430 --> 00:19:55,080
on the back end of
those apps, it'll

483
00:19:55,080 --> 00:19:59,130
usually just have some
dynamic request to the URL,

484
00:19:59,130 --> 00:20:01,390
to the bucket where
that image is stored.

485
00:20:01,390 --> 00:20:03,870
And so you can just pull
up those images instantly.

486
00:20:03,870 --> 00:20:07,320
And so I did some again, back
of the envelope calculations.

487
00:20:07,320 --> 00:20:09,600
You know I love that.

488
00:20:09,600 --> 00:20:12,250
And so I found there's roughly
over somewhere-- or at least

489
00:20:12,250 --> 00:20:16,110
at the time I pulled this data--
about 7 million listings, each

490
